    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Stevia eupatoria improperly include experiencing nausea, which is often due to its intense sweetness that can be overwhelming to the digestive system. Additionally, Stevia eupatoria may cause hypoglycemia, a drop in blood sugar levels, as it is known to inhibit the alpha-glucosidase enzyme, which can interfere with carbohydrate digestion and absorption. Furthermore, consuming Stevia eupatoria excessively can lead to diarrhea and other gastrointestinal issues, possibly due to its prebiotic properties that can alter gut bacteria balance. Some individuals may also develop allergic reactions, including skin rashes, itching, and swelling, as Stevia eupatoria is known to be a potential allergen. These side effects are often associated with the consumption of large doses of Stevia eupatoria or prolonged use.",
    "uses": "Stevia eupatoria is traditionally used to treat various health conditions. The plant's leaves have been used in folk medicine to help manage digestive issues, such as diarrhea and constipation. Stevia eupatoria is also said to have antimicrobial properties, which can help combat infections and promote wound healing. In addition, the plant has been used to help lower blood pressure and reduce inflammation. However, more research is needed to confirm the efficacy and safety of using Stevia eupatoria for medicinal purposes.",
    "taxonomy": "Stevia eupatoria is classified as a member of the Lamiaceae family, also known as the mint family. This classification is based on its botanical characteristics, such as its leaf shape and flower structure. As a member of the Lamiaceae family, Stevia eupatoria is a perennial herb native to the Mediterranean region. Its classification also places it within the Stevia genus, which is a group of plants known for their sweet-tasting leaves. Stevia eupatoria is closely related to other members of the Lamiaceae family, including the popular herbs mint and oregano.",
    "benefits": "Stevia eupatoria is known to have various health benefits, primarily attributed to its high concentration of stevioside and rebaudioside compounds. These compounds have been found to have potential anti-inflammatory properties and may help lower blood pressure. Research also suggests that Stevia eupatoria may help regulate blood sugar levels, making it a potential natural remedy for diabetes management. Additionally, its antibacterial properties may aid in preventing infections and promoting oral health. Further studies are needed to confirm the full extent of Stevia eupatoria's health benefits.",
    "parts": "Stevia eupatoria, the leaves and flowers of the plant are considered to be the medicinal parts. They contain compounds such as stevioside and rebaudioside, which have been used in traditional medicine for their sweetening and anti-inflammatory properties. The leaves are also used to treat digestive issues, such as diarrhea and stomach ulcers. The flowers are used to treat respiratory issues, such as bronchitis and coughs. Additionally, the roots of the plant are sometimes used in traditional medicine for their antimicrobial properties.",
    "intro": "Stevia eupatoria, also known as Stevia rebaudiana's lesser-known relative, is a plant species native to the tropical regions of the Americas, belonging to the sunflower family (Asteraceae). The leaves of Stevia eupatoria have been used for centuries in traditional medicine, offering potential health benefits such as reducing blood pressure, lowering blood sugar levels, and exhibiting anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties. The bioactive constituents of Stevia eupatoria include steviol glycosides, flavonoids, and phenolic acids, which contribute to its medicinal properties. Stevia eupatoria is commonly used to prepare herbal teas, infusions, and tinctures, as well as being added to foods and beverages as a natural sweetener."
